</tr><tr>
<td class="captioncell">
<p>New reconstruction of <i>Jamoytius kerwoodi</i></p><div class="credits blkctralign"><p>by <a href="references.html#Sansometal2010a">Sansom et al 2010</a></p></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
<p><i><span class="hilitdffcc99"><a name="Jamoytius"><b>Jamoytius</b></span></a></i><b>:</b> <i>J. kerwoodi</i></p>
<div class="taxrng"><p> Early Silurian of Scotland.</p></div>
<div class="taxphl"><p><a href="#Jamoytiiformes">Jamoytiiformes</a>: <a href="#Euphanerops"><i>Euphanerops</i></a> + *. </p></div>
<p><b>Characters:</b> W-shaped phosphatic scales, 10 or more pairs of branchial openings, optic capsules, a circular, subterminal mouth and a single terminal nasal opening. (<a href="references.html#Sansometal2010a">Sansom et al 2010</a>)</p>
<p><b>Comments:</b> <i>Jamoytius</i> is commonly considered to represent either a primitive anaspid or ancestral lamprey. Analysis by Sansom et al 2010 establishes sister taxon relationship with <i>Euphanerops</i>.. <a href="references.html#Sansometal2010a">Sansom et al 2010</a>. The generic name honours Paleozoic fish specialist J. A. Moy-Thomas (ref Dawkins, <i>The Ancestor's Tale</i>, via <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamoytius_kerwoodi">Wikipedia</a>). MAK111022</p>

